# ThreadSanitizer suppression file for FalkorDB tests
#
# This file suppresses known false positives and third-party races reported by
# ThreadSanitizer (TSAN) when running FalkorDB tests against a TSAN-instrumented
# Redis server.
#
# Suppression types:
#   race:<pattern>     — data races
#   signal:<pattern>   — signal-unsafe calls inside signal handlers
#   deadlock:<pattern> — lock-order-inversion (potential deadlock)
#   mutex:<pattern>    — mutex misuse (wrong thread, etc.)
#
# Patterns match against function names in the call stack.

# =============================================================================
# Section 1: Redis Server Internals
# =============================================================================
# Redis uses a single-threaded event loop with background I/O threads. TSAN
# flags many Redis internals that are safe under Redis's execution model.

# Kernel syscall — TSAN instrumentation artifact, not a real data race.
race:epoll_wait

# Redis event-loop I/O polling; protected by single-threaded event loop model.
race:aeApiPoll

# Redis event loop file-event management; single-threaded model.
race:aeCreateFileEvent
race:aeDeleteFileEvent
race:aeProcessEvents

# Redis module event-loop callback registration and writability check.
race:eventLoopCbWritable
race:RM_EventLoopAdd

# Redis background I/O thread (BIO) — job queue access serialised by Redis.
race:bioProcessBackgroundJobs

# Redis refcount operations — Redis objects use single-threaded refcounting.
race:incrRefCount
race:decrRefCount

# Redis key lookup and expire — protected by single-threaded event loop.
race:lookupKey
race:kvobjGetExpire

# Redis slowlog — appends happen from the main thread only.
race:slowlogCreateEntry

# Redis signal handlers call malloc/free/fopen/fclose (signal-unsafe) for
# crash logging and stack collection. These are known Redis design decisions.
signal:invoke_callback
signal:collect_stacktrace_data
signal:serverLogRaw
signal:printCrashReport
signal:logServerInfo

# =============================================================================
# Section 2: RediSearch Dependency
# =============================================================================
# RediSearch is an upstream dependency. These are internal RediSearch races
# that should be fixed upstream, not in FalkorDB.

# RediSearch thread pool init/teardown race — startup sequencing issue.
race:redisearch_thpool_init
race:redisearch_thpool_destroy

# RediSearch worker thread entry point — benign init race.
race:thread_do

# RediSearch inverted index lifecycle — concurrent add during free.
race:InvertedIndex_AddBlock
race:InvertedIndex_Free

# =============================================================================
# Section 3: FalkorDB False Positives (Documented Intentional Patterns)
# =============================================================================

# Graph_ReleaseLock sets _writelocked=false BEFORE calling pthread_rwlock_unlock.
# This is an intentional pattern documented in the source (graph.c:125-131) to
# prevent reader threads from being falsely identified as writers during the
# window between unlock and flag update.
race:Graph_ReleaseLock

# CircularBuffer_ItemCount reads item_count without the mutex. This is a benign
# best-effort read — the counter is only incremented under lock in
# CircularBuffer_Add, and a stale read is harmless (used for capacity checks).
race:CircularBuffer_ItemCount
race:CircularBuffer_Add

# Cron task management: _CRON_RemoveCurrentTask runs under CRON_LOCK.
# Cron_Run intentionally releases the lock during callback execution to prevent
# stalling (documented in cron.c:238-239), then writes current_task=NULL without
# the lock. This is an accepted pattern for the cron subsystem.
race:_CRON_RemoveCurrentTask
race:Cron_Run

# =============================================================================
# Section 4: Test Framework
# =============================================================================
# Races in test harness code, not in production FalkorDB code.

# acutest.h test framework uses a global check counter without synchronisation.
race:acutest_check_

# Test helper for thread-friendly IDs — test-only global counter.
race:get_thread_friendly_id
